PERMIT TRIGGER: Manual Removal (Vegetation Management)
Description: Hand pulling, lopping without machinery
Legal Triggers: entry_on_land
Potential Exemptions: CEQA Class 4 (Minor Alterations), NEPA Categorical Exclusion (often)

PERMIT TRIGGER: Mechanical Thinning (Vegetation Management)
Description: Use of masticators, chippers, skidders
Legal Triggers: soil_disturbance, noise_impact, emission_source
Likely Permits: NEPA/CEQA (if public land), Timber Harvest Plan (if commercial), Air District Burn Permit (if pile burning)

PERMIT TRIGGER: Prescribed Fire (Vegetation Management)
Description: Intentional ignition for fuel reduction
Legal Triggers: smoke_emission, risk_of_escape, take_risk
Likely Permits: Smoke Management Plan (Air District), Burn Permit (CAL FIRE/Fire Dept), CalVTP (if state funded)

PERMIT TRIGGER: Minor Grading (Earthwork And Grading)
Description: < 50 cubic yards, < 10% slope
Legal Triggers: soil_disturbance
Likely Permits: Local grading permit (check county thresholds)

PERMIT TRIGGER: Major Grading (Earthwork And Grading)
Description: > 50 cubic yards OR > 10% slope OR near water
Legal Triggers: significant_soil_disturbance, erosion_risk, sediment_discharge_risk
Likely Permits: Grading Permit, SWPPP (if > 1 acre disturbance), NPDES Construction General Permit

PERMIT TRIGGER: Bank Stabilization (Hydrologic Restoration)
Description: Work on stream banks (planting, bioengineering, riprap)
Legal Triggers: bed_bank_channel_alteration, discharge_dredge_fill, navigable_waters_impact
Likely Permits: CDFW 1602 LSAA, CWA Section 404 (USACE), CWA Section 401 (Regional Board)

PERMIT TRIGGER: Wetland Creation (Hydrologic Restoration)
Description: Excavation or filling to create/restore wetland
Legal Triggers: discharge_dredge_fill, change_in_land_use
Likely Permits: CWA Section 404, CWA Section 401, Coastal Development Permit (if in zone)

LEGAL RESTRAINT RULE: No Legal Advice
Rule: NEVER provide legal advice or definitive conclusions about legal outcomes.
Rationale: Only an attorney can apply law to specific facts. AI provides information based on general rules.
PROHIBITED PHRASES: You can..., You are allowed to..., This is legal..., You do not need a permit..., The law allows...
REQUIRED FRAMING: Regulations typically require..., Generally, X implies Y..., The statute states..., Consult with agency staff or legal counsel for determination.

LEGAL RESTRAINT RULE: No Guarantees
Rule: NEVER guarantee a permit outcome or timeline.
Rationale: Permitting is discretionary and fact-specific.
PROHIBITED PHRASES: Your permit will be approved..., This will take 30 days..., This is a guaranteed exemption...
REQUIRED FRAMING: Statutory review periods are X days..., Approval typically depends on...

JURISDICTION RULE: Federal Lands Surface
Primary Authority: Federal Land Management Agency (USFS, BLM, NPS, USFWS)
Authority Overlay: State environmental laws often apply via 'Savings Clauses' or cooperative federalism (e.g., CWA Section 401)
Key Principle: Federal law preempts state law where conflict exists, but states can often be stricter

JURISDICTION RULE: State Lands
Primary Authority: State Land Management Agency (State Parks, SLC)
Authority Overlay: Federal layout ONLY if Federal Nexus exists (ESA, CWA, Federal Funding)
Key Principle:

JURISDICTION RULE: Private Lands
Primary Authority: Local Government (County/City) + State Regulatory Agencies
Authority Overlay: Apply ONLY if Federal Nexus exists (Waters of US, Listed Species, Federal Funding)
Key Principle:

JURISDICTION RULE: Tribal Lands Trust
Primary Authority: Tribal Government + BIA (Federal Trustee)
Authority Overlay: 
Key Principle: Tribal Sovereignty

FEDERAL NEXUS TRIGGER: FUNDING. Condition: Project receives ANY federal funding (grants, loans, cost-share). Consequence: NEPA compliance required (Lead Federal Agency must analyze). Examples: FEMA hazard mitigation grants, NRCS EQIP funding, USFS state & private forestry grants.

FEDERAL NEXUS TRIGGER: PERMITTING_CWA_404. Condition: Discharge of dredged or fill material into Waters of the United States (WOTUS). Consequence: US Army Corps of Engineers permit required + NEPA + ESA Section 7. Examples: Stream crossing replacement, Wetland restoration with fill, Levee modification.

FEDERAL NEXUS TRIGGER: PERMITTING_ESA. Condition: Take of Federally Listed Species (on private land). Consequence: ESA Section 10 Incidental Take Permit (HCP) OR Section 7 if other federal nexus exists. Examples: Grading in endangered frog habitat, Timber harvest in spotted owl territory.

FEDERAL NEXUS TRIGGER: FEDERAL_ACTION. Condition: Action requiring federal approval or on federal land. Consequence: Full federal compliance suite (NEPA, NHPA, ESA). Examples: Right-of-way across BLM land, Special Use Permit on National Forest.

LEGAL FRAMEWORK (International Frameworks): UN Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD)
Type: international_treaty
Implications for restoration:
  - Frame restoration as contributing to national CBD targets
  - Track biodiversity outcomes, not just area restored
  - Prioritize sites with high biodiversity value

LEGAL FRAMEWORK (International Frameworks): UN Decade on Ecosystem Restoration (2021-2030)
Type: international_initiative
Implications for restoration:
  - Map interventions to SDG indicators
  - Engage local stakeholders in planning
  - Document carbon co-benefits

LEGAL FRAMEWORK (International Frameworks): Paris Agreement (UNFCCC)
Type: international_treaty
Implications for restoration:
  - Estimate carbon sequestration potential
  - Align with national NDC commitments
  - Document climate adaptation benefits

LEGAL FRAMEWORK (Us Federal Laws): Endangered Species Act (ESA)
Legal code: 16 U.S.C. § 1531 et seq.
Agency: USFWS, NMFS
Legal constraints:
  - No actions that result in 'take' of listed species without permit
  - Section 7 consultation triggered if federal action 'may affect' listed species
  - Habitat Conservation Plan (HCP) required for incidental take on non-federal land
Key provisions:
  - section_7: Federal agency consultation for listed species
  - section_9: Prohibition on take of listed species
  - section_10: Incidental take permits for non-federal actions

LEGAL FRAMEWORK (Us Federal Laws): Clean Water Act (CWA)
Legal code: 33 U.S.C. § 1251 et seq.
Agency: EPA, Army Corps of Engineers
Legal constraints:
  - Section 404 permit required for discharge of dredged/fill material into Waters of the US (WOTUS)
  - No net loss of wetland acreage/function policy applies
  - Mitigation required for unavoidable impacts (hierarchy: avoid, minimize, compensate)
Key provisions:
  - section_404: Permits for discharge of dredged or fill material into waters
  - section_401: State water quality certification
  - section_402: NPDES permits for point source discharges
Implications for restoration:
  - Wetland restoration may require 404 permit
  - Stream restoration needs Army Corps consultation
  - Riparian buffers must meet water quality standards

LEGAL FRAMEWORK (Us Federal Laws): National Environmental Policy Act (NEPA)
Legal code: 42 U.S.C. § 4321 et seq.
Agency: Council on Environmental Quality (CEQ)
Legal constraints:
  - Federal Nexus (funding, permit, or land) triggers NEPA compliance
  - Documentation level (CX, EA, EIS) depends on 'significance' of impacts
  - Alternatives analysis required for EA and EIS levels

LEGAL FRAMEWORK (Us Federal Laws): Wilderness Act of 1964
Legal code: 16 U.S.C. § 1131 et seq.
Agency: USFS, NPS, BLM, USFWS

LEGAL FRAMEWORK (Us Federal Laws): National Historic Preservation Act (NHPA)
Legal code: 54 U.S.C. § 300101 et seq.
Agency: Advisory Council on Historic Preservation
Legal constraints:
  - Archaeological survey may be required
  - Tribal consultation for traditional cultural properties
  - Avoid/mitigate impacts to historic resources
Key provisions:
  - section_106: Federal undertakings require review for historic properties

LEGAL FRAMEWORK (Us Federal Laws): America the Beautiful (30x30) Initiative
Agency: DOI, USDA, NOAA
Type: executive_initiative
Implications for restoration:
  - Prioritize sites contributing to 30x30 goals
  - Track conservation outcomes
  - Align with state and tribal conservation plans

LEGAL FRAMEWORK (California State Laws): California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA)
Legal code: Public Resources Code § 21000 et seq.
Agency: Lead agency (varies)
Legal constraints:
  - Discretionary approval by public agency triggers CEQA
  - Exemptions must be verified (cannot rely on 'minor' label without checking exceptions)
  - Mitigation monitoring required for MND and EIR projects

LEGAL FRAMEWORK (California State Laws): California Endangered Species Act (CESA)
Legal code: Fish & Game Code § 2050 et seq.
Agency: California Department of Fish and Wildlife (CDFW)
Legal constraints:
  - No take of state-listed species
  - Separate from federal ESA (both may apply)
  - CDFW consultation for impacts to listed species
Key provisions:
  - section_2081: Incidental take permits
  - section_2080.1: Consistency determinations with federal ESA

LEGAL FRAMEWORK (California State Laws): Lake and Streambed Alteration Agreement
Legal code: Fish & Game Code § 1602
Agency: CDFW
Legal constraints:
  - Notification to CDFW required before work
  - Agreement with conditions for work
  - Applies to even dry streambeds
Implications for restoration:
  - Stream restoration requires 1602 agreement
  - Erosion control work near streams needs notification
  - Planting in riparian zone may trigger review

LEGAL FRAMEWORK (California State Laws): California 30x30 Initiative
Agency: California Natural Resources Agency
Type: executive_order
Implications for restoration:
  - Restoration contributes to conservation goals
  - Priority for climate-resilient ecosystems
  - Tribal co-management encouraged

LEGAL FRAMEWORK (California State Laws): California Vegetation Treatment Program (CalVTP)
Agency: CAL FIRE, Board of Forestry
Type: programmatic_eir

INDIGENOUS RIGHTS: Free, Prior, and Informed Consent (FPIC)
Source: UN Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples (UNDRIP)
Definition: Indigenous peoples have the right to give or withhold consent to projects affecting their lands and resources
Key principles:
  - FREE: Consent given voluntarily, without coercion
  - PRIOR: Consent obtained before project begins
  - INFORMED: Full information provided in accessible format
  - CONSENT: Right to say no, not just consultation
ABSOLUTE CONSTRAINTS (non-negotiable):
  [WARNING] NEVER recommend restoration on tribal lands without explicit FPIC
  [WARNING] Flag all projects in/near indigenous territories
  [WARNING] Default to community-led restoration, not top-down planning

INDIGENOUS RIGHTS: Government-to-Government Consultation
Requirements:
  - Federal agencies must consult with tribes on significant actions
  - Meaningful dialogue, not just notification
  - Consider tribal treaty rights and traditional uses

INDIGENOUS RIGHTS: Indigenous Data Sovereignty
Constraints:
  - Do not collect data on tribal lands without permission
  - Acknowledge indigenous knowledge in outputs
  - Share benefits of data analysis with communities

INDIGENOUS RIGHTS: California Native American Tribes
Implications for restoration:
  - Many fire-affected areas are ancestral lands
  - Cultural burning is traditional practice
  - Tribes are key partners in restoration

ETHICAL CONSIDERATION: Risk Of Oversimplification
Risk: AI may miss ecosystem nuances
Examples:
  - Microhabitat variation not visible in satellite data
  - Soil conditions require on-site assessment
  - Species interactions complex and unpredictable
Mitigation strategies:
  - Frame as DECISION SUPPORT, not autonomous decision-making
  - ALWAYS require expert validation before implementation
  - Acknowledge uncertainty in all recommendations
  - Include confidence scores and limitations

ETHICAL CONSIDERATION: Displacement Of Local Knowledge
Risk: Traditional ecological knowledge not captured in satellite data
Examples:
  - Indigenous burning practices more effective than AI suggestions
  - Local landowners know specific site conditions
  - Community has historical knowledge of ecosystem change
Mitigation strategies:
  - Recommend community consultation as MANDATORY step
  - Frame AI as COMPLEMENTARY to local knowledge, not replacement
  - Include TEK integration points in workflow
  - Respect expertise of local practitioners

ETHICAL CONSIDERATION: Unintended Consequences
Risk: AI recommendation harms adjacent ecosystem
Examples:
  - Downstream impacts of hydrological changes
  - Introduction of species that become invasive
  - Disruption of wildlife corridors
Mitigation strategies:
  - Holistic landscape-level assessment
  - Uncertainty quantification in all outputs
  - Adaptive management framework
  - Monitoring requirements for all interventions

ETHICAL CONSIDERATION: Misuse Prevention
Risk: Tool used for greenwashing, land grabs, or displacement
Examples:
  - Restoration claims used to displace communities
  - Carbon offset projects violating indigenous rights
  - Biodiversity 'restoration' that harms existing ecosystems
Mitigation strategies:
  - Clear terms of use and ethical guidelines
  - Transparency in all recommendations
  - Built-in checks for indigenous land overlap
  - Cannot recommend removal of communities

ETHICAL CONSIDERATION: Data Bias
Geographic bias:
  Issue: High-resolution data more available in wealthy regions
  Mitigation: Acknowledge data limitations, use consistent data sources

LEGAL TEMPLATE for NATIONAL FOREST
Applicable laws: NEPA, NFMA, ESA, NHPA, Clean Water Act
Permits likely required:
  - NEPA documentation
  - Section 7 if listed species
  - 1602 for streams
Constraints:
  - Consult with USFS ranger district
  - Follow forest plan standards
  - Check for wilderness boundaries

LEGAL TEMPLATE for WILDERNESS AREA
Applicable laws: Wilderness Act, NEPA, ESA
Permits likely required:
  - Minimum Requirements Analysis
  - Research permit if needed
Constraints:
  - ONLY natural regeneration
  - No mechanized equipment
  - Hand tools only
  - Minimal intervention philosophy

LEGAL TEMPLATE for NATIONAL PARK
Applicable laws: NPS Organic Act, NEPA, ESA, NHPA
Permits likely required:
  - NPS project review
  - NEPA document
  - Archaeological survey
Constraints:
  - NPS approval required
  - Native species only
  - Preserve natural character

LEGAL TEMPLATE for STATE PARK
Applicable laws: CEQA, CESA, 1602
Permits likely required:
  - CEQA document
  - State Parks authorization
Constraints:
  - State Parks approval required
  - Follow park management plan

LEGAL TEMPLATE for PRIVATE LAND
Applicable laws: CEQA (if permit trigger), County zoning, CWA if wetlands
Permits likely required:
  - Varies by county
  - 1602 if streams
  - 404 if wetlands
Constraints:
  - Respect property rights
  - Check easements
  - Follow county regulations

LEGAL TEMPLATE for TRIBAL LAND
Applicable laws: Tribal law primary, NEPA if federal funding, ESA if listed species
Permits likely required:
  - Tribal Council approval
  - FPIC documentation
Constraints:
  - FPIC REQUIRED before any action
  - Tribal sovereignty respected
  - Community-led planning only
